channel.title: What to do with spare time
channel.description:
I've always dreaded having to ask this question, I never thought I'd have to.. But I really am not sure what to do.
I'm a college student, I go to school two days a week. That leaves 5 days for me to do anything. I haven't got a job, I've looked but my area isn't that accepting to kids fresh out of high school. That's no excuse, but I'm not in need of a job anyways.
I don't want to return to playing games(Runescape specifically), because that took up a large chunk of my life already.
I'm social but not the type to go out every day of the week.
I've resorted to watching TED Talks and fulfilling graphic requests on another forum, but that gets boring fast
What do you guys do with your spare time :confused:

item.title: What to do with spare time
item.dc:creator: @m.dog311 m.dog311
item.description:
@m.dog311 wrote:

[quote=“abraham2119, post:18, topic:416968”]Depends on what your goal is: for pure strength training, bodyweight exercises are sufficient but for hypertrophy, they are not.

Don’t listen to m.dog311; instead of buying equipment, get a gym membership – not that expensive really (I’ve seen Ballys with $10/month offers).

Anyways, I currently do a three day split (triceps and chest, biceps and back, and shoulder and legs) and workout every other day. As for my caloric intake, on workout days I eat around 600+ my BMR and try to save all of my (complex) carbs (and calories really) for post workout (think of a IF carb cycling hybrid sort of thing) and on rest days a caloric deficit of around 300-600 with little to no carbs. Simple carbs I absolutely avoid except around 15 minutes pre-workout for energy. Stick to 1g of protein per pound.

I’ve been at it “strictly” (little bit of cheating) for around 3 months and have had great gains: I’ve put on 15 pounds of muscle and cut from ~12% to ~9% body fat.[/quote]
All the gyms in my area are absolutely shit, or horribly expensive ($40+ a month)

Read full topic

item.dc:creator: @abraham2119 abraham2119
item.description:
@abraham2119 wrote:

Depends on what your goal is: for pure strength training, bodyweight exercises are sufficient but for hypertrophy, they are not.

Don’t listen to m.dog311; instead of buying equipment, get a gym membership – not that expensive really (I’ve seen Ballys with $10/month offers).

Anyways, I currently do a three day split (triceps and chest, biceps and back, and shoulder and legs) and workout every other day. As for my caloric intake, on workout days I eat around 600+ my BMR and try to save all of my (complex) carbs (and calories really) for post workout (think of a IF carb cycling hybrid sort of thing) and on rest days a caloric deficit of around 300-600 with little to no carbs. Simple carbs I absolutely avoid except around 15 minutes pre-workout for energy. Stick to 1g of protein per pound.

I’ve been at it “strictly” (little bit of cheating) for around 3 months and have had great gains: I’ve put on 15 pounds of muscle and cut from ~12% to ~9% body fat.
